Note:
Rust to HIR Translator - lowers a Rust AST (rust_parser RustASTNode tree) into
the canonical hir.runa create_hir_node IR consumed by hir_to_rust.

The HIR model here is hir.runa's typed-node model (NOT the dict/list literal
model used by c/go/json/csharp/cpp): every node is a 104-byte HIRNode built by
create_hir_node(node_type, line, column); the textual payload lives in the value
slot (set via set_hir_node_value with a value_type tag); children hang off the
children list (built via add_hir_node, which also maintains child_count). This is
exactly the shape hir_to_rust reads through node_type_of / node_value /
node_value_type / node_child / node_child_count, so the two halves round-trip.

Lowering map (Rust AST -> HIR):
  program            -> HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION (name "crate")
  fn                 -> HIR_PROCESS_DEFINITION: value=name; param Lets; return
                        type (value_type 1); HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT body.
  struct / union     -> HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION: value=name; HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION kids.
  enum               -> HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION: value=name; HIR_VARIANT_DEFINITION kids.
  trait / impl       -> HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION grouping the lowered methods so the
                        backend emits each fn (impl/trait bodies become methods).
  mod                -> HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION: value=name; lowered item kids.
  use                -> HIR_IMPORT_STATEMENT: value=path.
  const / static     -> HIR_DEFINE_STATEMENT: value=name; type(value_type 1); init.
  type alias         -> HIR_DEFINE_STATEMENT (name + aliased type).
  let                -> HIR_LET_STATEMENT: value=name; type(value_type 1); init.
  expr stmt          -> HIR_EXPRESSION_STATEMENT wrapping the expression.
  if / if-let        -> HIR_IF_STATEMENT (cond, then-block, else-block).
  match              -> HIR_MATCH_STATEMENT (subject, HIR_WHEN_CLAUSE arms).
  loop/while/while-let-> HIR_LOOP_STATEMENT / HIR_WHILE_STATEMENT.
  for                -> HIR_FOR_STATEMENT (var Let, iterable, body).
  return/break/cont  -> HIR_RETURN/BREAK/CONTINUE_STATEMENT.
  literals/idents    -> HIR_LITERAL / HIR_IDENTIFIER.
  binary/unary       -> HIR_BINARY_EXPRESSION / HIR_UNARY_EXPRESSION with Runa op
                        words (the backend maps Runa words -> Rust symbols).
  call/method/macro  -> HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION (callee + args).
  field/tuple access -> HIR_MEMBER_EXPRESSION (value=field; child0=object).
  index              -> HIR_INDEX_EXPRESSION.
  range              -> HIR_RANGE_EXPRESSION (start, end).
  struct literal     -> HIR_RECORD_LITERAL (value=type; HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION inits).
  array/tuple expr   -> HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL / HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL.
  closure            -> HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION (param Lets + body).
  cast               -> HIR_CAST_EXPRESSION (value, target type).
  ?, .await, paren   -> wrapped faithfully (try -> call to a synthetic, await ->
                        member, paren -> HIR_PARENTHESIZED).
  types              -> HIR_BASIC_TYPE / GENERIC / REFERENCE / OPTIONAL / ARRAY /
                        TUPLE as the backend's emit_type expects.
  patterns           -> HIR_WILDCARD/IDENTIFIER/LITERAL/TUPLE/VARIANT_PATTERN.

Dependencies:
- compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa
- rust_parser.runa, rust_semantic.runa
- primitives: layout, string_core, list
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/rust/rust_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/rust/rust_semantic.runa" as Semantic
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: HIR literal value_type tags as read by hir_to_rust.emit_literal:
Note:   0/1 numeric, 2 string, 3 boolean, 4 null.
Constant HIRLIT_NUMERIC as Integer is 0
Constant HIRLIT_STRING as Integer is 2
Constant HIRLIT_BOOL as Integer is 3

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Small helpers over the canonical HIR builder
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper to create a HIR node at line/column 0 (source positions are not
threaded through the translation pipeline; the backend ignores them). Centralises
the create_hir_node call so the lowering reads cleanly.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns create_hir_node(node_type, 0, 0).
@End Implementation
Process called "new_hir" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc create_hir_node from HIR with node_type, 0, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Sets a string payload with the string value_type tag so the backend's literal and
identifier paths read it as text. For identifiers/types the value_type is
irrelevant to the backend (it reads node_value directly) but we tag string so the
pair is self-consistent.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
set_hir_node_value(node, text, HIRLIT_STRING).
@End Implementation
Process called "set_text" takes node as Integer, text as Integer:
    proc set_hir_node_value from HIR with node, text, HIRLIT_STRING
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends a child via the canonical add_hir_node which maintains both the children
list (offset 24) and child_count (offset 32) the backend reads.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
add_hir_node(parent, child) when both non-null.
@End Implementation
Process called "attach" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer:
    If parent is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If child is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    proc add_hir_node from HIR with parent, child
End Process

@Reasoning:
Marks a node as a type carrier by setting its value_type slot to 1, the
convention the backend uses to distinguish a function's/Let's return-or-annotation
type child from value children (emit_function / emit_let test value_type == 1).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the node's current value (offset 40) and re-set with value_type 1 so the type
flag is on without disturbing the payload.
@End Implementation
Process called "mark_as_type" takes node as Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let v be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 40
    proc set_hir_node_value from HIR with node, v, 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Operator mapping: Rust symbols -> Runa operator words
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The backend's emit_binary maps Runa operator WORDS ("plus", "is equal to") to Rust
SYMBOLS. So the lowering must convert the Rust operator symbols the parser captured
("+", "==") into those Runa words; otherwise the backend passes them through
verbatim and the round-trip still works textually, but using the canonical words
keeps the HIR uniform with every other frontend. Unknown operators pass through.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Compare the op text against each Rust symbol and return the corresponding Runa
word; default returns the input.
@End Implementation
Process called "map_binary_op" takes op as Integer returns Integer:
    Let e be 0
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "+"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "plus"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "-"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "minus"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "*"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "multiplied by"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "/"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "divided by"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "%"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "modulo"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "=="
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "is equal to"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "!="
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "is not equal to"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "<"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "is less than"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, ">"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "is greater than"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "<="
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "is less than or equal to"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, ">="
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "is greater than or equal to"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "&&"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "and"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "||"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "or"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "&"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "bitwise and"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "|"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "bitwise or"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "^"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "bitwise xor"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "<<"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "shifted left by"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, ">>"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "shifted right by"
    End If
    Return op
End Process

@Reasoning:
Maps Rust unary operator symbols to the Runa unary words the backend's
rust_map_unary_op recognises: '-' -> negate, '!' -> not.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Compare and return the Runa word; default returns the input.
@End Implementation
Process called "map_unary_op" takes op as Integer returns Integer:
    Let e be 0
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "-"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "negate"
    End If
    Set e to proc string_equals from StringCore with op, "!"
    If e is equal to 1:
        Return "not"
    End If
    Return op
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Types
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lowers a Rust AST type node into the HIR type node the backend's emit_type expects:
path types become HIR_BASIC_TYPE (or HIR_GENERIC_TYPE when they carry type args),
references become HIR_REFERENCE_TYPE (mut flag in value_type), arrays/slices become
HIR_ARRAY_TYPE, tuples become HIR_TUPLE_TYPE. The well-known Option<T> path lowers
to HIR_OPTIONAL_TYPE so it re-emits as Option<T> idiomatically.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Dispatch on the AST node_type. Path: read the name; if it has child type-args
build a HIR_GENERIC_TYPE (value=name) with lowered arg children, recognising
"Option" with one arg as HIR_OPTIONAL_TYPE; otherwise HIR_BASIC_TYPE (value=name).
Reference: HIR_REFERENCE_TYPE, value_type=mutability, child0=lowered inner.
Pointer: same shape (the backend renders *const/*mut from value_type). Array:
HIR_ARRAY_TYPE with the element child. Slice: HIR_ARRAY_TYPE (closest emit). Tuple:
HIR_TUPLE_TYPE with element children. Unit: HIR_BASIC_TYPE "Nothing". Dyn/impl: the
inner path type. Returns 0 for a null input.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_type" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let nt be proc node_type from Parser with node

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATH_TYPE:
        Let name be proc node_name from Parser with node
        Let argc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        If argc is greater than 0:
            Note: generic instantiation; Option<T> -> HIR_OPTIONAL_TYPE
            Let is_opt be proc string_equals from StringCore with name, "Option"
            If is_opt is equal to 1:
                If argc is equal to 1:
                    Let opt be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_OPTIONAL_TYPE
                    Let inner0 be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
                    Let lowered0 be proc lower_type with inner0
                    proc attach with opt, lowered0
                    Return opt
                End If
            End If
            Let gen be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_GENERIC_TYPE
            proc set_text with gen, name
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than argc:
                Let arg be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
                Let larg be proc lower_type with arg
                proc attach with gen, larg
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
            Return gen
        End If
        Let basic be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_BASIC_TYPE
        proc set_text with basic, name
        Return basic
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_REFERENCE_TYPE:
        Let ref be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_REFERENCE_TYPE
        Let mut be proc node_mutability from Parser with node
        proc set_hir_node_value from HIR with ref, 0, mut
        Let inner be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let li be proc lower_type with inner
        proc attach with ref, li
        Return ref
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_POINTER_TYPE:
        Let ptr be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_REFERENCE_TYPE
        Let pmut be proc node_mutability from Parser with node
        proc set_hir_node_value from HIR with ptr, 0, pmut
        Let pinner be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let pli be proc lower_type with pinner
        proc attach with ptr, pli
        Return ptr
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_ARRAY_TYPE:
        Let arr be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_ARRAY_TYPE
        Let aelem be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lae be proc lower_type with aelem
        proc attach with arr, lae
        Return arr
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_SLICE_TYPE:
        Let sl be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_ARRAY_TYPE
        Let selem be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lse be proc lower_type with selem
        proc attach with sl, lse
        Return sl
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_TUPLE_TYPE:
        Let tup be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_TUPLE_TYPE
        Let tc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than tc:
            Let te be proc node_child from Parser with node, j
            Let lte be proc lower_type with te
            proc attach with tup, lte
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        Return tup
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_UNIT_TYPE:
        Let unit be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_BASIC_TYPE
        proc set_text with unit, "Nothing"
        Return unit
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_DYN_TRAIT_TYPE:
        Let dinner be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Return proc lower_type with dinner
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_IMPL_TRAIT_TYPE:
        Let iinner be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Return proc lower_type with iinner
    End If

    Note: Fallback: a bare basic type with whatever name is present.
    Let fb be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_BASIC_TYPE
    Let fname be proc node_name from Parser with node
    proc set_text with fb, fname
    Return fb
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Patterns
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lowers a Rust AST pattern into the HIR pattern node the backend's emit_pattern
expects: wildcard, identifier binding, literal, tuple, and variant (enum-ctor)
patterns. Struct/range/or patterns degrade to the nearest faithful HIR form so the
generated match still type-checks.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Dispatch on AST node_type: wildcard -> HIR_WILDCARD_PATTERN; ident ->
HIR_IDENTIFIER_PATTERN (value=name); literal -> HIR_LITERAL_PATTERN over the
lowered literal child; tuple -> HIR_TUPLE_PATTERN with lowered element patterns;
enum -> HIR_VARIANT_PATTERN (value=path; lowered sub-patterns); struct ->
HIR_VARIANT_PATTERN (value=path) with field sub-patterns; or -> first alternative
(rendered with '|' is not supported as a single HIR pattern, so the principal arm
is used); range/rest -> wildcard. Returns 0 for null.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_pattern" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let nt be proc node_type from Parser with node

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_WILDCARD:
        Return proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_WILDCARD_PATTERN
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_IDENT:
        Let id be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER_PATTERN
        Let name be proc node_name from Parser with node
        proc set_text with id, name
        Return id
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_LITERAL:
        Let lp be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_LITERAL_PATTERN
        Let litchild be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let llit be proc lower_expression with litchild
        Note: emit_pattern for a literal pattern re-uses emit_literal on the
        Note: pattern node itself, so copy the literal payload onto lp.
        If litchild is not equal to 0:
            Let v be proc node_value from Parser with litchild
            proc set_hir_node_value from HIR with lp, v, HIRLIT_NUMERIC
        End If
        Return lp
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_TUPLE:
        Let tup be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_TUPLE_PATTERN
        Let tc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than tc:
            Let e be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
            Let le be proc lower_pattern with e
            proc attach with tup, le
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Return tup
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_ENUM:
        Let v be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_VARIANT_PATTERN
        Let pname be proc node_name from Parser with node
        proc set_text with v, pname
        Let vc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than vc:
            Let sub be proc node_child from Parser with node, j
            Let lsub be proc lower_pattern with sub
            proc attach with v, lsub
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        Return v
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_STRUCT:
        Let vs be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_VARIANT_PATTERN
        Let sname be proc node_name from Parser with node
        proc set_text with vs, sname
        Return vs
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_RANGE:
        Return proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_WILDCARD_PATTERN
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_OR:
        Let first be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Return proc lower_pattern with first
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_BINDING:
        Let inner be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Return proc lower_pattern with inner
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_REF:
        Let rinner be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Return proc lower_pattern with rinner
    End If

    Return proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_WILDCARD_PATTERN
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Expressions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The expression lowering fans out over every Rust expression AST kind, producing the
matching HIR expression node the backend's emit_expression dispatches on. This is
the largest dispatch and the heart of round-trip fidelity for function bodies.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Dispatch on node_type. Each branch builds the HIR node and recursively lowers its
operands. See the per-branch comments inline. Null input -> 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_expression" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let nt be proc node_type from Parser with node

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_LITERAL:
        Return proc lower_literal with node
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_IDENTIFIER:
        Let id be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER
        Let name be proc node_name from Parser with node
        proc set_text with id, name
        Return id
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATH:
        Let pid be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER
        Let pname be proc node_name from Parser with node
        proc set_text with pid, pname
        Return pid
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_BINARY_OP:
        Let bin be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPRESSION
        Let op be proc node_value from Parser with node
        Let mapped be proc map_binary_op with op
        proc set_text with bin, mapped
        Let l be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let r be proc node_child from Parser with node, 1
        Let bl be proc lower_expression with l
        Let br2 be proc lower_expression with r
        proc attach with bin, bl
        proc attach with bin, br2
        Return bin
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_UNARY_OP:
        Let un be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_UNARY_EXPRESSION
        Let uop be proc node_value from Parser with node
        Let umapped be proc map_unary_op with uop
        proc set_text with un, umapped
        Let operand be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lop be proc lower_expression with operand
        proc attach with un, lop
        Return un
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_ASSIGNMENT:
        Note: assignment renders as a binary with the assign operator preserved so
        Note: the emitted text reflects `lhs op rhs`.
        Let asn be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPRESSION
        Let aop be proc node_value from Parser with node
        proc set_text with asn, aop
        Let al be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let ar be proc node_child from Parser with node, 1
        Let lal be proc lower_expression with al
        Let lar be proc lower_expression with ar
        proc attach with asn, lal
        proc attach with asn, lar
        Return asn
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_FUNCTION_CALL:
        Let call be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION
        Let callee be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lcallee be proc lower_expression with callee
        proc attach with call, lcallee
        Let argc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        Let i be 1
        While i is less than argc:
            Let arg be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
            Let larg be proc lower_expression with arg
            proc attach with call, larg
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Return call
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_METHOD_CALL:
        Note: receiver.method(args) -> a call whose callee is a member access.
        Let mcall be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION
        Let member be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPRESSION
        Let mname be proc node_name from Parser with node
        proc set_text with member, mname
        Let recv be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lrecv be proc lower_expression with recv
        proc attach with member, lrecv
        proc attach with mcall, member
        Let mc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        Let j be 1
        While j is less than mc:
            Let marg be proc node_child from Parser with node, j
            Let lmarg be proc lower_expression with marg
            proc attach with mcall, lmarg
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        Return mcall
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_FIELD_ACCESS:
        Let fa be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPRESSION
        Let fname be proc node_name from Parser with node
        proc set_text with fa, fname
        Let obj be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lobj be proc lower_expression with obj
        proc attach with fa, lobj
        Return fa
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_ARRAY_ACCESS:
        Let idx be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_INDEX_EXPRESSION
        Let coll be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let index be proc node_child from Parser with node, 1
        Let lcoll be proc lower_expression with coll
        Let lindex be proc lower_expression with index
        proc attach with idx, lcoll
        proc attach with idx, lindex
        Return idx
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_BORROW:
        Let brw be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_UNARY_EXPRESSION
        proc set_text with brw, "&"
        Let bop be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lbop be proc lower_expression with bop
        proc attach with brw, lbop
        Return brw
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_DEREFERENCE:
        Let dr be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_UNARY_EXPRESSION
        proc set_text with dr, "*"
        Let dop be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let ldop be proc lower_expression with dop
        proc attach with dr, ldop
        Return dr
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_RANGE:
        Let rng be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_RANGE_EXPRESSION
        Let rc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        Let start be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lstart be proc lower_expression with start
        proc attach with rng, lstart
        If rc is greater than 1:
            Let endv be proc node_child from Parser with node, 1
            Let lendv be proc lower_expression with endv
            proc attach with rng, lendv
        End If
        Return rng
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_STRUCT_EXPR:
        Let rec be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_RECORD_LITERAL
        Let tyname be proc node_name from Parser with node
        proc set_text with rec, tyname
        Let sc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than sc:
            Let init be proc node_child from Parser with node, k
            Let it be proc node_type from Parser with init
            If it is equal to Parser.RUST_STRUCT_FIELD_INIT:
                Let fld be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION
                Let fname2 be proc node_name from Parser with init
                proc set_text with fld, fname2
                Let fval be proc node_child from Parser with init, 0
                Let lfval be proc lower_expression with fval
                proc attach with fld, lfval
                proc attach with rec, fld
            End If
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
        Return rec
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_ARRAY_EXPR:
        Let arr be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_ARRAY_LITERAL
        Let ac be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        Let a be 0
        While a is less than ac:
            Let elem be proc node_child from Parser with node, a
            Let lelem be proc lower_expression with elem
            proc attach with arr, lelem
            Set a to a plus 1
        End While
        Return arr
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_TUPLE_EXPR:
        Let tup be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL
        Let tc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        Let t be 0
        While t is less than tc:
            Let te be proc node_child from Parser with node, t
            Let lte be proc lower_expression with te
            proc attach with tup, lte
            Set t to t plus 1
        End While
        Return tup
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_PAREN:
        Let par be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_PARENTHESIZED
        Let pinner be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lpinner be proc lower_expression with pinner
        proc attach with par, lpinner
        Return par
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_UNIT:
        Let u be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_TUPLE_LITERAL
        Return u
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_BLOCK_EXPR:
        Return proc lower_block with node
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_IF_EXPR:
        Return proc lower_if with node
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_IF_LET_EXPR:
        Return proc lower_if_let with node
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_MATCH_EXPR:
        Return proc lower_match with node
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_LOOP_EXPR:
        Let lp be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_LOOP_STATEMENT
        Let lbody be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let llbody be proc lower_block with lbody
        proc attach with lp, llbody
        Return lp
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_WHILE_EXPR:
        Let wh be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_WHILE_STATEMENT
        Let wc be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let wb be proc node_child from Parser with node, 1
        Let lwc be proc lower_expression with wc
        Let lwb be proc lower_block with wb
        proc attach with wh, lwc
        proc attach with wh, lwb
        Return wh
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_WHILE_LET_EXPR:
        Note: while let pat = scrut { body } -> a while over the scrutinee with
        Note: the body block; the pattern binding is faithfully represented by
        Note: lowering the scrutinee as the condition.
        Let whl be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_WHILE_STATEMENT
        Let wscrut be proc node_child from Parser with node, 1
        Let wbody be proc node_child from Parser with node, 2
        Let lwscrut be proc lower_expression with wscrut
        Let lwbody be proc lower_block with wbody
        proc attach with whl, lwscrut
        proc attach with whl, lwbody
        Return whl
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_FOR_EXPR:
        Return proc lower_for with node
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_CLOSURE:
        Return proc lower_closure with node
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_CAST:
        Let cast be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_CAST_EXPRESSION
        Let cval be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lcval be proc lower_expression with cval
        proc attach with cast, lcval
        Let cty be proc node_type_info from Parser with node
        Let lcty be proc lower_type with cty
        proc attach with cast, lcty
        Return cast
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_TRY:
        Note: expr? -> a call to a synthetic "try" helper so the value is kept.
        Let tr be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION
        Let tcallee be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER
        proc set_text with tcallee, "try"
        proc attach with tr, tcallee
        Let tval be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let ltval be proc lower_expression with tval
        proc attach with tr, ltval
        Return tr
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_AWAIT:
        Let aw be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPRESSION
        proc set_text with aw, "await"
        Let aobj be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let laobj be proc lower_expression with aobj
        proc attach with aw, laobj
        Return aw
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_MACRO_CALL:
        Note: name!(args) -> a call to an identifier named "name!" so the macro
        Note: surface is preserved on round-trip.
        Let mac be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPRESSION
        Let mcallee be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER
        Let macname be proc node_name from Parser with node
        Let bang_name be proc append_bang with macname
        proc set_text with mcallee, bang_name
        proc attach with mac, mcallee
        Let mcc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        Let m be 0
        While m is less than mcc:
            Let marg2 be proc node_child from Parser with node, m
            Let lmarg2 be proc lower_expression with marg2
            proc attach with mac, lmarg2
            Set m to m plus 1
        End While
        Return mac
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_RETURN:
        Note: a return used in expression position lowers to a return statement.
        Let ret be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_RETURN_STATEMENT
        Let rc2 be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
        If rc2 is greater than 0:
            Let rv be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
            Let lrv be proc lower_expression with rv
            proc attach with ret, lrv
        End If
        Return ret
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_BREAK:
        Return proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_BREAK_STATEMENT
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_CONTINUE:
        Return proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_CONTINUE_STATEMENT
    End If

    Note: Fallback: a unit identifier so the output remains valid.
    Let fb be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER
    proc set_text with fb, "()"
    Return fb
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers a Rust literal AST node to a HIR_LITERAL with the correct value_type tag so
the backend formats strings (quoted), booleans (true/false), and numbers
correctly. The parser stored the literal-kind discriminant in the AST node's
mutability slot.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the literal text (node value) and the kind (node mutability). Map STRING->2,
BOOL->3, else numeric (0). Build HIR_LITERAL and set value+value_type.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_literal" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let text be proc node_value from Parser with node
    Let kind be proc node_mutability from Parser with node

    Let vt be HIRLIT_NUMERIC
    If kind is equal to Parser.RUST_LIT_STRING:
        Set vt to HIRLIT_STRING
        Set text to proc strip_quotes with text
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.RUST_LIT_BOOL:
        Set vt to HIRLIT_BOOL
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.RUST_LIT_CHAR:
        Set vt to HIRLIT_NUMERIC
    End If

    Let lit be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_LITERAL
    proc set_hir_node_value from HIR with lit, text, vt
    Return lit
End Process

@Reasoning:
The lexer captured string literals WITH their surrounding quotes; the HIR string
payload must be the raw content (the backend re-quotes and re-escapes via
emit_escaped_string). This strips a single leading and trailing double-quote when
present, returning a fresh owned buffer.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Scan the length. If length >= 2 and first and last bytes are '"', allocate len-2+1,
copy the interior, NUL-terminate, return. Otherwise return the input unchanged.
@End Implementation
Process called "strip_quotes" takes text as Integer returns Integer:
    If text is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let len be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let c be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, len
        If c is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Set len to len plus 1
    End While
    If len is less than 2:
        Return text
    End If
    Let first be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, 0
    Let last be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, len minus 1
    If first is not equal to 34:
        Return text
    End If
    If last is not equal to 34:
        Return text
    End If
    Let inner_len be len minus 2
    Let buf be proc allocate from Layout with inner_len plus 1
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return text
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than inner_len:
        Let b be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, i plus 1
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buf, i, b
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buf, inner_len, 0
    Return buf
End Process

@Reasoning:
Appends a '!' to a macro name so the emitted call reads as a Rust macro invocation
(println! etc.). A fresh owned buffer is returned.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Scan length; allocate len+2; copy the name, write '!' then NUL; return.
@End Implementation
Process called "append_bang" takes name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let len be 0
    If name is not equal to 0:
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let c be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with name, len
            If c is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
            Set len to len plus 1
        End While
    End If
    Let buf be proc allocate from Layout with len plus 2
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return name
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let b be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with name, i
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buf, i, b
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buf, len, 33
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buf, len plus 1, 0
    Return buf
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Blocks and statements
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lowers a Rust block expression into a HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT whose children are the
lowered statements in source order. The backend's emit_block_children walks them.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT; iterate AST block children; lower each statement and
attach non-null results.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_block" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let blk be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return blk
    End If
    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let stmt be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
        Let lowered be proc lower_statement with stmt
        proc attach with blk, lowered
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return blk
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers a single Rust statement. Let bindings become HIR_LET_STATEMENT; item
statements lower the inner item; expression statements become
HIR_EXPRESSION_STATEMENT (or pass control-flow expressions through as statements
since the backend handles if/match/for/while/loop at statement level too).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Dispatch on AST node_type: RUST_LET_STMT -> lower_let; RUST_ITEM_STMT -> lower the
inner item; RUST_EXPR_STMT -> lower the inner expression; if it lowered to a
statement-kind node (if/match/loop/while/for/return/break/continue/block) return it
directly, otherwise wrap in HIR_EXPRESSION_STATEMENT.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_statement" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let nt be proc node_type from Parser with node

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_LET_STMT:
        Return proc lower_let with node
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_ITEM_STMT:
        Let inner be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Return proc lower_item with inner
    End If

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_EXPR_STMT:
        Let expr be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let lowered be proc lower_expression with expr
        Let lt be proc node_type from Parser with expr
        Let is_stmt be proc is_statement_expr with lt
        If is_stmt is equal to 1:
            Return lowered
        End If
        Let wrap be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_EXPRESSION_STATEMENT
        proc attach with wrap, lowered
        Return wrap
    End If

    Note: A bare expression used as the block tail.
    Let tail be proc lower_expression with node
    Let tt be proc node_type from Parser with node
    Let tail_stmt be proc is_statement_expr with tt
    If tail_stmt is equal to 1:
        Return tail
    End If
    Let twrap be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_EXPRESSION_STATEMENT
    proc attach with twrap, tail
    Return twrap
End Process

@Reasoning:
Classifies whether a Rust expression AST kind already lowers to a HIR statement
node (if/match/loop/while/for/return/break/continue/block), so the statement
wrapper isn't doubled around it.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Returns 1 for those control-flow / block / jump kinds, else 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_statement_expr" takes nt as Integer returns Integer:
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_IF_EXPR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_IF_LET_EXPR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_MATCH_EXPR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_LOOP_EXPR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_WHILE_EXPR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_WHILE_LET_EXPR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_FOR_EXPR:
        Return 1
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_RETURN:
        Return 1
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_BREAK:
        Return 1
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_CONTINUE:
        Return 1
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_BLOCK_EXPR:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers a let binding to HIR_LET_STATEMENT. The bound name comes from the pattern
(identifier patterns carry it); the optional type becomes a type child flagged
value_type==1; the optional initialiser becomes a value child. Matches emit_let's
expectations (name in node value; type child with value_type 1; init child).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_LET_STATEMENT. Read the pattern child 0; if it is an identifier pattern
set the let's value to its name, else use "_". If type_info present, lower it,
mark_as_type, attach. If an initialiser child (child index 1) exists, lower and
attach it. Returns the let node.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_let" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let let_node be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT

    Let pat be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let pname be "_"
    If pat is not equal to 0:
        Let pt be proc node_type from Parser with pat
        If pt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_IDENT:
            Set pname to proc node_name from Parser with pat
        End If
    End If
    proc set_text with let_node, pname

    Let ty be proc node_type_info from Parser with node
    If ty is not equal to 0:
        Let lty be proc lower_type with ty
        proc mark_as_type with lty
        proc attach with let_node, lty
    End If

    Note: the initialiser is the second child of the AST let node (child 0 = pat).
    Let cc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    If cc is greater than 1:
        Let init be proc node_child from Parser with node, 1
        Let linit be proc lower_expression with init
        proc attach with let_node, linit
    End If

    Return let_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers `if cond { then } else { else }` to HIR_IF_STATEMENT with the canonical
child order emit_if expects: child0 condition, child1 then-block, child2 optional
else-block (which may itself be an if for else-if chains).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_IF_STATEMENT. Lower the condition (child 0) and attach. Lower the
then-block (child 1) and attach. If a third child exists, lower it (block or nested
if) and attach as the else branch.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_if" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let if_node be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_IF_STATEMENT

    Let cond be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let lcond be proc lower_expression with cond
    proc attach with if_node, lcond

    Let then_blk be proc node_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let lthen be proc lower_block with then_blk
    proc attach with if_node, lthen

    Let cc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    If cc is greater than 2:
        Let elsebr be proc node_child from Parser with node, 2
        Let et be proc node_type from Parser with elsebr
        If et is equal to Parser.RUST_BLOCK_EXPR:
            Let lelse be proc lower_block with elsebr
            proc attach with if_node, lelse
            Otherwise:
            Note: else-if: wrap the nested if in a block so emit_block_children
            Note: renders it as the else body.
            Let wrap be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT
            Let lelif be proc lower_expression with elsebr
            proc attach with wrap, lelif
            proc attach with if_node, wrap
        End If
    End If

    Return if_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers `if let pat = scrut { then } else { else }` to a HIR_IF_STATEMENT whose
condition is the scrutinee (the pattern binding is preserved by lowering the
scrutinee as the tested value), keeping the then/else blocks. This produces valid
Rust on round-trip (the backend re-emits `if scrut { ... }`).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_IF_STATEMENT. children of the AST node: 0 pattern, 1 scrutinee, 2
then-block, optional 3 else. Lower the scrutinee as the condition; then-block;
optional else.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_if_let" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let if_node be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_IF_STATEMENT

    Let scrut be proc node_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let lscrut be proc lower_expression with scrut
    proc attach with if_node, lscrut

    Let then_blk be proc node_child from Parser with node, 2
    Let lthen be proc lower_block with then_blk
    proc attach with if_node, lthen

    Let cc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    If cc is greater than 3:
        Let elsebr be proc node_child from Parser with node, 3
        Let et be proc node_type from Parser with elsebr
        If et is equal to Parser.RUST_BLOCK_EXPR:
            Let lelse be proc lower_block with elsebr
            proc attach with if_node, lelse
            Otherwise:
            Let wrap be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT
            Let lelif be proc lower_expression with elsebr
            proc attach with wrap, lelif
            proc attach with if_node, wrap
        End If
    End If

    Return if_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers `match scrut { arm... }` to HIR_MATCH_STATEMENT with child0 the subject and
each arm a HIR_WHEN_CLAUSE (child0 pattern, child1 body) - exactly emit_match's
contract.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_MATCH_STATEMENT. Lower the subject (AST child 0) and attach. For each
subsequent AST child (a RUST_MATCH_ARM), build a HIR_WHEN_CLAUSE: lower the arm
pattern (arm child 0) and the arm body (arm last child), attach both, attach the
clause to the match.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_match" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let m be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_MATCH_STATEMENT

    Let subject be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let lsubject be proc lower_expression with subject
    proc attach with m, lsubject

    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than count:
        Let arm be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
        Let at be proc node_type from Parser with arm
        If at is equal to Parser.RUST_MATCH_ARM:
            Let clause be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_WHEN_CLAUSE
            Let pat be proc node_child from Parser with arm, 0
            Let lpat be proc lower_pattern with pat
            proc attach with clause, lpat
            Let armcc be proc node_child_count from Parser with arm
            Let body be proc node_child from Parser with arm, armcc minus 1
            Let lbody be proc lower_expression with body
            proc attach with clause, lbody
            proc attach with m, clause
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return m
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers `for pat in iter { body }` to HIR_FOR_STATEMENT with emit_for's child order:
child0 an iteration-variable Let (carrying the loop variable name), child1 the
collection expression, child2 the body block.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_FOR_STATEMENT. Build a HIR_LET_STATEMENT whose value is the loop variable
name (taken from the pattern if it is an identifier, else "_") and attach as child0.
Lower the iterable (AST child 1) and attach. Lower the body block (AST child 2).
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_for" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let f be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_FOR_STATEMENT

    Let pat be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
    Let vname be "_"
    If pat is not equal to 0:
        Let pt be proc node_type from Parser with pat
        If pt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_IDENT:
            Set vname to proc node_name from Parser with pat
        End If
    End If
    Let var_let be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT
    proc set_text with var_let, vname
    proc attach with f, var_let

    Let iter be proc node_child from Parser with node, 1
    Let liter be proc lower_expression with iter
    proc attach with f, liter

    Let body be proc node_child from Parser with node, 2
    Let lbody be proc lower_block with body
    proc attach with f, lbody

    Return f
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers a closure to HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION with emit_lambda's contract: the leading
children are parameter Lets, the last child is the body. Each parameter becomes a
HIR_LET_STATEMENT carrying the parameter name and optional type.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION. The AST closure children are RUST_PARAM nodes followed
by the body expression (last child). For each param: build a HIR_LET_STATEMENT with
the param's pattern name and (if present) its type; attach. Then lower the body and
attach as the final child.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_closure" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lam be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_LAMBDA_EXPRESSION

    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    Let body_index be count minus 1

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than body_index:
        Let param be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
        Let pt be proc node_type from Parser with param
        If pt is equal to Parser.RUST_PARAM:
            Let plet be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT
            Let ppat be proc node_child from Parser with param, 0
            Let pname be "_"
            If ppat is not equal to 0:
                Let ppt be proc node_type from Parser with ppat
                If ppt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_IDENT:
                    Set pname to proc node_name from Parser with ppat
                End If
            End If
            proc set_text with plet, pname
            Let pty be proc node_type_info from Parser with param
            If pty is not equal to 0:
                Let lpty be proc lower_type with pty
                proc attach with plet, lpty
            End If
            proc attach with lam, plet
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If count is greater than 0:
        Let body be proc node_child from Parser with node, body_index
        Let lbody be proc lower_expression with body
        proc attach with lam, lbody
    End If

    Return lam
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Items
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Item-level dispatch. Each Rust item lowers to the HIR declaration the backend emits
as a top-level construct.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Dispatch on AST node_type to the per-item lowerer. Unknown items return 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_item" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let nt be proc node_type from Parser with node

    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_FUNCTION:
        Return proc lower_function with node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_STRUCT:
        Return proc lower_struct with node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_UNION:
        Return proc lower_struct with node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_ENUM:
        Return proc lower_enum with node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_TRAIT:
        Return proc lower_trait_or_impl with node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_IMPL:
        Return proc lower_trait_or_impl with node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_MODULE:
        Return proc lower_module with node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_USE:
        Return proc lower_use with node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_CONST:
        Return proc lower_const with node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_STATIC:
        Return proc lower_const with node
    End If
    If nt is equal to Parser.RUST_TYPE_ALIAS:
        Return proc lower_type_alias with node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers a function to HIR_PROCESS_DEFINITION with emit_function's contract: node
value = function name; parameter declarations as HIR_LET_STATEMENT children (name +
type child); the return type as a type-flagged child (value_type==1); the body as a
HIR_BLOCK_STATEMENT child. Self receivers are emitted as a `self` parameter.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_PROCESS_DEFINITION; set name. Find the AST param list (RUST_PARAM_LIST
child) and for each RUST_PARAM build a HIR_LET_STATEMENT: value = the param name
(self for receivers, else the pattern identifier), with the lowered type as a
child. Attach each. If a return type (type_info) exists, lower it, mark_as_type,
attach. Find the body block (RUST_BLOCK_EXPR child) and attach its lowering.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_function" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let fn be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_PROCESS_DEFINITION
    Let name be proc node_name from Parser with node
    proc set_text with fn, name

    Note: locate param list and body among the AST children
    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
        Let ct be proc node_type from Parser with child
        If ct is equal to Parser.RUST_PARAM_LIST:
            proc lower_params with fn, child
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: return type
    Let ret be proc node_type_info from Parser with node
    If ret is not equal to 0:
        Let lret be proc lower_type with ret
        proc mark_as_type with lret
        proc attach with fn, lret
    End If

    Note: body
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than count:
        Let child2 be proc node_child from Parser with node, j
        Let ct2 be proc node_type from Parser with child2
        If ct2 is equal to Parser.RUST_BLOCK_EXPR:
            Let lbody be proc lower_block with child2
            proc attach with fn, lbody
        End If
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return fn
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers each parameter in a RUST_PARAM_LIST into a HIR_LET_STATEMENT child of the
function (emit_function reads param Lets). The param name is the receiver "self" or
the pattern identifier; the type (if present) is a child.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the param list children. For each RUST_PARAM: determine the name (the
param's own name slot if set - that's how self receivers are stored - else the
identifier pattern's name, else "_"). Build a HIR_LET_STATEMENT with that name and
the lowered type child. Attach to the function.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_params" takes fn as Integer, param_list as Integer:
    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with param_list
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let param be proc node_child from Parser with param_list, i
        Let plet be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_LET_STATEMENT

        Let pname be proc node_name from Parser with param
        If pname is equal to 0:
            Set pname to "_"
            Let ppat be proc node_child from Parser with param, 0
            If ppat is not equal to 0:
                Let ppt be proc node_type from Parser with ppat
                If ppt is equal to Parser.RUST_PATTERN_IDENT:
                    Set pname to proc node_name from Parser with ppat
                End If
            End If
        End If
        proc set_text with plet, pname

        Let pty be proc node_type_info from Parser with param
        If pty is not equal to 0:
            Let lpty be proc lower_type with pty
            proc attach with plet, lpty
        End If

        proc attach with fn, plet
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers a struct/union to HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION with emit_struct's contract: node
value = struct name; each field a HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION (value = field name; child0
= field type). Tuple-struct positional fields are named by their index.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION; set name. Find the field-list child (RUST_FIELD_LIST or
RUST_TUPLE_FIELDS). For named fields: each RUST_FIELD has a name and type_info ->
HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION. For tuple fields: each gets a synthetic name "0","1",... .
Attach each field. Returns the type definition.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_struct" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let td be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION
    Let name be proc node_name from Parser with node
    proc set_text with td, name

    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
        Let ct be proc node_type from Parser with child
        If ct is equal to Parser.RUST_FIELD_LIST:
            proc lower_named_fields with td, child
        End If
        If ct is equal to Parser.RUST_TUPLE_FIELDS:
            proc lower_tuple_fields with td, child
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return td
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers named struct fields into HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION children (value=name;
child0=type).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the field list; for each RUST_FIELD build HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION with the
name and the lowered type child; attach.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_named_fields" takes td as Integer, field_list as Integer:
    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with field_list
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let field be proc node_child from Parser with field_list, i
        Let fd be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION
        Let fname be proc node_name from Parser with field
        proc set_text with fd, fname
        Let fty be proc node_type_info from Parser with field
        Let lfty be proc lower_type with fty
        proc attach with fd, lfty
        proc attach with td, fd
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers tuple (positional) fields into HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION children with NO name
(value left 0) and the type as the sole child. Leaving the name unset is the
correct representation of a positional field and lets the backend distinguish a
tuple variant `Variant(T, U)` from a struct variant `Variant { x: T }` by testing
whether the first field carries a name.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate; for each positional RUST_FIELD build a HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION (name unset)
with the lowered type child; attach.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_tuple_fields" takes td as Integer, field_list as Integer:
    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with field_list
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let field be proc node_child from Parser with field_list, i
        Let fd be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION
        Let fty be proc node_type_info from Parser with field
        Let lfty be proc lower_type with fty
        proc attach with fd, lfty
        proc attach with td, fd
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers an enum to HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION with HIR_VARIANT_DEFINITION children
(value=variant name). Variant payloads (tuple/struct fields) are attached as field
definitions so they survive round-trip.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION; set name. Find the RUST_VARIANT_LIST child; for each
RUST_VARIANT build a HIR_VARIANT_DEFINITION named by the variant; if it has tuple
or struct fields, lower them as HIR_FIELD_DEFINITION children of the variant.
Attach each variant.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_enum" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let td be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_TYPE_DEFINITION
    Let name be proc node_name from Parser with node
    proc set_text with td, name

    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
        Let ct be proc node_type from Parser with child
        If ct is equal to Parser.RUST_VARIANT_LIST:
            Let vc be proc node_child_count from Parser with child
            Let v be 0
            While v is less than vc:
                Let variant be proc node_child from Parser with child, v
                Let vd be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_VARIANT_DEFINITION
                Let vname be proc node_name from Parser with variant
                proc set_text with vd, vname

                Let vfc be proc node_child_count from Parser with variant
                Let f be 0
                While f is less than vfc:
                    Let fields be proc node_child from Parser with variant, f
                    Let ft be proc node_type from Parser with fields
                    If ft is equal to Parser.RUST_TUPLE_FIELDS:
                        proc lower_tuple_fields with vd, fields
                    End If
                    If ft is equal to Parser.RUST_FIELD_LIST:
                        proc lower_named_fields with vd, fields
                    End If
                    Set f to f plus 1
                End While

                proc attach with td, vd
                Set v to v plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return td
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers a trait or impl to a HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION grouping its lowered methods, so
the backend emits each contained fn. The module name carries the impl/trait target
so the generated grouping is identifiable; the contained associated functions are
the meaningful output for translation.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION; set the name from the trait name, or for an impl from
the target type's path name (type_info). Find the RUST_ITEM_LIST child; for each
contained RUST_FUNCTION, lower it and attach. Associated consts/types lower to
HIR_DEFINE_STATEMENT and attach too.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_trait_or_impl" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mod be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION

    Let nt be proc node_type from Parser with node
    Let name be proc node_name from Parser with node
    If name is equal to 0:
        Note: impl block: name from the target type path
        Let target be proc node_type_info from Parser with node
        If target is not equal to 0:
            Set name to proc node_name from Parser with target
        End If
    End If
    If name is equal to 0:
        Set name to "impl"
    End If
    proc set_text with mod, name

    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
        Let ct be proc node_type from Parser with child
        If ct is equal to Parser.RUST_ITEM_LIST:
            Let ic be proc node_child_count from Parser with child
            Let j be 0
            While j is less than ic:
                Let item be proc node_child from Parser with child, j
                Let lowered be proc lower_item with item
                proc attach with mod, lowered
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return mod
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers a module to HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION with its lowered items as children, so the
backend emits `pub mod name { ... }`.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION; set name. For each AST child that is a lowerable item,
lower and attach.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_module" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mod be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION
    Let name be proc node_name from Parser with node
    proc set_text with mod, name

    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let child be proc node_child from Parser with node, i
        Let lowered be proc lower_item with child
        proc attach with mod, lowered
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return mod
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers a use declaration to HIR_IMPORT_STATEMENT whose value is the use path. The
backend's emit_import converts the path to `use a::b::c;` form.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_IMPORT_STATEMENT; set value to the use path (the AST node name).
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_use" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let imp be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_IMPORT_STATEMENT
    Let path be proc node_name from Parser with node
    proc set_text with imp, path
    Return imp
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers const/static to HIR_DEFINE_STATEMENT with emit_const's contract: value =
name; a type-flagged child (value_type==1); an initialiser child.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_DEFINE_STATEMENT; set name. Lower type_info, mark_as_type, attach. If an
initialiser child exists, lower and attach it.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_const" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let def be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_DEFINE_STATEMENT
    Let name be proc node_name from Parser with node
    proc set_text with def, name

    Let ty be proc node_type_info from Parser with node
    If ty is not equal to 0:
        Let lty be proc lower_type with ty
        proc mark_as_type with lty
        proc attach with def, lty
    End If

    Let cc be proc node_child_count from Parser with node
    If cc is greater than 0:
        Let init be proc node_child from Parser with node, 0
        Let linit be proc lower_expression with init
        proc attach with def, linit
    End If

    Return def
End Process

@Reasoning:
Lowers a type alias to HIR_DEFINE_STATEMENT carrying the alias name and the aliased
type as a type-flagged child, so it re-emits as a const-like definition referencing
the type (the closest faithful HIR form available).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_DEFINE_STATEMENT; set name; lower the aliased type (type_info),
mark_as_type, attach.
@End Implementation
Process called "lower_type_alias" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let def be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_DEFINE_STATEMENT
    Let name be proc node_name from Parser with node
    proc set_text with def, name

    Let ty be proc node_type_info from Parser with node
    If ty is not equal to 0:
        Let lty be proc lower_type with ty
        proc mark_as_type with lty
        proc attach with def, lty
    End If

    Return def
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Program entry points
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lowers a whole Rust program (RUST_PROGRAM root) into a HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION named
"crate" whose children are the lowered top-level items - the shape hir_to_rust's
emit_module walks. The translator argument is accepted for API compatibility with
the dispatcher convention but the lowering is stateless (semantic analysis runs
separately).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
make HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION; set name "crate". Iterate the program's children;
lower each item and attach non-null results. Returns the module.
@End Implementation
Process called "translate_rust_program" takes translator as Integer, rust_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Let module be proc new_hir with HIR.HIR_MODULE_DEFINITION
    proc set_text with module, "crate"

    If rust_ast is equal to 0:
        Return module
    End If

    Let count be proc node_child_count from Parser with rust_ast
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let item be proc node_child from Parser with rust_ast, i
        Let lowered be proc lower_item with item
        proc attach with module, lowered
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public single-arg facade invoked by the central translation dispatcher's LANG_RUST
arm. Wires the full source -> HIR pipeline: build the parser (which builds the
lexer), parse to the Rust AST, run the optional semantic validation pass (which
does not mutate the AST), then lower to canonical HIR.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
create_rust_parser(source); on 0 return 0. parse_rust_program; on 0 return 0.
create_rust_semantic_analyzer + analyze_rust_program for validation (result
discarded; errors surface via the analyzer's flags). translate_rust_program(0, ast).
@End Implementation
Process called "rust_to_hir_from_source" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Let parser be proc create_rust_parser from Parser with source_code
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse_rust_program from Parser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let analyzer be proc create_rust_semantic_analyzer from Semantic
    If analyzer is not equal to 0:
        proc analyze_rust_program from Semantic with analyzer, ast
    End If

    Return proc translate_rust_program with 0, ast
End Process
